  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious crime with significant penalties. Here are the key potential consequences:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Imprisonment: Up to 20 years per offense\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from illegal transactions\n\n2. Financial Penalties:\n- Fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Additional civil monetary penalties may apply\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n- Enhanced penalties if connected to specific crimes like drug trafficking\n\nThe exact penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Prior criminal history\n- Whether the laundering was part of other criminal activities\n\nThese penalties are primarily defined under:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary Transaction in Criminally Derived Property)\n\nProsecution and sentencing can involve federal agencies like the Department of Justice and financial regulators.",
